name: benzaldoxime,syn

The formyl group is expected to increase the melting point due to its ability to engage in dipole-dipole interactions, as well as providing potential sites for hydrogen bonding with the N-OH group. This could potentially raise the melting point by approximately 20°C. The N-OH group (hydroxyimino) can additionally form hydrogen bonds, which may raise the melting point substantially by around 50°C due to the strong intermolecular forces involved. However, the molecule exists as a syn isomer, which may have a less optimal packing in the crystal lattice compared to a potential anti isomer, leading to a possibly slightly lower melting point than if it were the anti version. Hence, we might slightly reduce the overall increase in melting point to account for this effect, by around 5°C.
